{
  "texts": [
    "For instance, modifications in GANs such as perceptual image hashing (Neff et al. 2017), the mixture of distributions in the generator (Wu et al. 2018b), and VAEGAN-based architectures (Segato et al. 2020) have been used to alleviate the mode collapse problem.",
    "In biomedical imaging applications, GANs can also cause feature hallucinations when generating new synthetic data (Laino et al. 2022).",
    "Hallucination in GANs refers to the generation of novel, unwanted artificial features or missing significant features in synthetically generated images that can lead to the risk of misdiagnosing diseases (Wolterink et al. 2021).",
    "The hallucinated features are generated due to the problem of mode collapse in GANs.",
    "Hallucinated features are usually generated in the synthetic images when performing the image-to-image translation task (Cohen et al. 2018)."
  ]
}